":"In the load path this is typically a <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Xaml.XamlObjectWriter&gt;</ph>.","pos":[6091,6164],"source":" In the load path this is typically a <xref:System.Xaml.XamlObjectWriter>."},{"content":"In the save path this is typically a <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Xaml.XamlXmlWriter&gt;</ph>.","pos":[6165,6235],"source":" In the save path this is typically a <xref:System.Xaml.XamlXmlWriter>."},{"content":"Each report the service context as an internal XAML service provider context class that implements a service provider pattern.","pos":[6236,6362]},{"content":"For more information about the available services and what they represent, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Type Converters and Markup Extensions for XAML<ept id=\"p1\">](../../../docs/framework/xaml-services/type-converters-and-markup-extensions-for-xaml.md)</ept>.","pos":[6363,6580],"source":" For more information about the available services and what they represent, see [Type Converters and Markup Extensions for XAML](../../../docs/framework/xaml-services/type-converters-and-markup-extensions-for-xaml.md)."},{"content":"Your markup extension class must use a public access level; XAML processors must always be able to instantiate the markup extension's support class in order to use its services.","pos":[6587,6764]},{"pos":[6815,6870],"content":"Defining the Support Type for a Custom Markup Extension","linkify":"Defining the Support Type for a Custom Markup Extension","nodes":[{"content":"Defining the Support Type for a Custom Markup Extension","pos":[0,55]}]},{"content":"When you use .NET Framework XAML Services or frameworks that build on .NET Framework XAML Services, you have two choices for how to name the markup extension support type.","pos":[6874,7045]},{"content":"The type name is relevant to how XAML object writers attempt to access and invoke a markup extension support type when they encounter a markup extension usage in XAML.","pos":[7046,7213]},{"content":"Use one of the following naming strategies:","pos":[7214,7257]},{"content":"Name the type name to be an exact match to the XAML markup usage token.","pos":[7267,7338]},{"content":"For example, to support a <ph id=\"ph1\">`{Collate ...}`</ph> extension usage, name the support type <ph id=\"ph2\">`Collate`</ph>.","pos":[7339,7430],"source":" For example, to support a `{Collate ...}` extension usage, name the support type `Collate`."},{"content":"Name the type name to be the usage string token plus the suffix <ph id=\"ph1\">`Extension`</ph>.","pos":[7440,7516],"source":"Name the type name to be the usage string token plus the suffix `Extension`."},{"content":"For example, to support a <ph id=\"ph1\">`{Collate ...}`</ph> extension usage, name the support type <ph id=\"ph2\">`CollateExtension`</ph>.","pos":[7517,7617],"source":" For example, to support a `{Collate ...}` extension usage, name the support type `CollateExtension`."},{"pos":[7624,7765],"content":"The order of lookup is to look for the <ph id=\"ph1\">`Extension`</ph>-suffixed class name first and then look for the class name without the <ph id=\"ph2\">`Extension`</ph> suffix.","source":"The order of lookup is to look for the `Extension`-suffixed class name first and then look for the class name without the `Extension` suffix."},{"content":"From the markup usage perspective, including the <ph id=\"ph1\">`Extension`</ph> suffix as part of the usage is valid.","pos":[7772,7870],"source":"From the markup usage perspective, including the `Extension` suffix as part of the usage is valid."},{"content":"However, this behaves as if <ph id=\"ph1\">`Extension`</ph> is truly part of the class name, and XAML object writers would fail to resolve a markup extension support class for that usage if the support class did not have the <ph id=\"ph2\">`Extension`</ph> suffix.","pos":[7871,8095],"source":" However, this behaves as if `Extension` is truly part of the class name, and XAML object writers would fail to resolve a markup extension support class for that usage if the support class did not have the `Extension` suffix."},{"pos":[8105,8128],"content":"The Default Constructor","linkify":"The Default Constructor","nodes":[{"content":"The Default Constructor","pos":[0,23]}]},{"content":"For all markup extension support types, you should expose a public default constructor.","pos":[8132,8219]},{"content":"A default constructor is required for any case where a XAML object writer instantiates the markup extension from an object element usage.","pos":[8220,8357]},{"content":"Supporting object element usage is a fair expectation for a markup extension, particularly for serialization.","pos":[8358,8467]},{"content":"However, you can implement a markup extension without a public constructor if you only intend to support attribute usages of the markup extension.","pos":[8468,8614]},{"content":"If your markup extension usage has no arguments, the default constructor is required to support usage.","pos":[8621,8723]},{"pos":[8826,8901],"content":"Constructor Patterns and Positional Arguments for a Custom Markup Extension","linkify":"Constructor Patterns and Positional Arguments for a Custom Markup Extension","nodes":[{"content":"Constructor Patterns and Positional Arguments for a Custom Markup Extension","pos":[0,75]}]},{"content":"For a markup extension with intended argument usage, the public constructors must correspond to the modes of the intended usage.","pos":[8905,9033]},{"content":"In other words, if your markup extension is designed to require one positional argument as a valid usage, you should support a public constructor with one input parameter that takes the positional argument.","pos":[9034,9240]},{"content":"For example, suppose the <ph id=\"ph1\">`Collate`</ph> markup extension is intended to support only a mode where there is one positional argument that represents its mode, specified as a <ph id=\"ph2\">`CollationMode`</ph> enumeration constant.","pos":[9247,9451],"source":"For example, suppose the `Collate` markup extension is intended to support only a mode where there is one positional argument that represents its mode, specified as a `CollationMode` enumeration constant."},{"content":"In this case, there should be a constructor with the following form:","pos":[9452,9520]},{"content":"At a basic level, the arguments passed to a markup extension are a string because they are being forwarded from the markup's attribute values.","pos":[9594,9736]},{"content":"You can make all of your arguments strings and work with input at that level.","pos":[9737,9814]},{"content":"However, you do have access to certain processing that occurs before the markup extension arguments are passed to the support class.","pos":[9815,9947]},{"content":"The processing works conceptually as if the markup extension is an object to be created, and then its member values are set.","pos":[9954,10078]},{"content":"Each specified property to set is evaluated similar to how a specified member can be set on a created object when XAML is parsed.","pos":[10079,10208]},{"content":"There are two important differences:","pos":[10209,10245]},{"content":"As noted previously, a markup extension support type does not need to have a default constructor in order to be instantiated in XAML.","pos":[10255,10388]},{"content":"Its object construction is deferred until its possible arguments in the text syntax are tokenized and evaluated as either positional or named arguments, and the appropriate constructor is called at that time.","pos":[10389,10597]},{"content":"Markup extensions usages can be nested.","pos":[10607,10646]},{"content":"The innermost markup extension is evaluated first.","pos":[10647,10697]},{"content":"Therefore, you can assume such a usage and declare one of the construction parameters to be a type that requires a value converter (such as a markup extension) to produce.","pos":[10698,10869]},{"content":"A reliance on such processing was shown in the previous example.","pos":[10876,10940]},{"content":"The .NET Framework XAML Services XAML object writer processes enumeration constant names into enumerated values at a native level.","pos":[10941,11071]},{"content":"Processing text syntax of a markup extension positional parameter can also rely on a type converter that is associated with the type that is in the construction argument.","pos":[11078,11248]},{"content":"The arguments are called positional arguments because the order in which the tokens in the usage is encountered corresponds to the positional order of the constructor parameter to which they are assigned.","pos":[11255,11459]},{"content":"For example, consider the following constructor signature:","pos":[11460,11518]},{"content":"A XAML processor expects two positional arguments for this markup extension.","pos":[11612,11688]},{"content":"If there was a usage <ph id=\"ph1\">`{Collate AlphaUp,{x:Reference circularFile}}`</ph>, the <ph id=\"ph2\">`AlphaUp`</ph> token is sent to the first parameter and evaluated as a <ph id=\"ph3\">`CollationMode`</ph> enumeration named constant.","pos":[11689,11871],"source":" If there was a usage `{Collate AlphaUp,{x:Reference circularFile}}`, the `AlphaUp` token is sent to the first parameter and evaluated as a `CollationMode` enumeration named constant."},{"content":"The result of the inner <ph id=\"ph1\">`x:Reference`</ph> is sent to the second parameter and evaluated as an object.","pos":[11872,11969],"source":" The result of the inner `x:Reference` is sent to the second parameter and evaluated as an object."},{"content":"In the XAML specified rules for markup extension syntax and processing, the comma is the delimiter between arguments, whether those arguments are positional arguments or named arguments.","pos":[11976,12162]},{"pos":[12172,12211],"content":"Duplicate Arity of Positional Arguments","linkify":"Duplicate Arity of Positional Arguments","nodes":[{"content":"Duplicate Arity of Positional Arguments","pos":[0,39]}]},{"content":"If a XAML object writer encounters a markup extension usage with positional arguments, and there are multiple constructor arguments that take that number of arguments (a duplicate arity), that is not necessarily an error.","pos":[12215,12436]},{"content":"The behavior depends on a customizable XAML schema context setting, <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Xaml.XamlSchemaContextSettings.SupportMarkupExtensionsWithDuplicateArity%2A&gt;</ph>.","pos":[12437,12595],"source":" The behavior depends on a customizable XAML schema context setting, <xref:System.Xaml.XamlSchemaContextSettings.SupportMarkupExtensionsWithDuplicateArity%2A>."},{"content":"If <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Xaml.XamlSchemaContextSettings.SupportMarkupExtensionsWithDuplicateArity%2A&gt;</ph> is <ph id=\"ph2\">`true`</ph>, a XAML object writer should not throw an exception only for reasons of duplicate arity.","pos":[12596,12787],"source":" If <xref:System.Xaml.XamlSchemaContextSettings.SupportMarkupExtensionsWithDuplicateArity%2A> is `true`, a XAML object writer should not throw an exception only for reasons of duplicate arity."},{"content":"Behavior beyond that point is not strictly defined.","pos":[12788,12839]},{"content":"The basic design assumption is that the schema context has type information available for the specific parameters and can attempt explicit casts that match the duplicate candidates to see which signature might be the best match.","pos":[12840,13068]},{"content":"An exception might still be thrown if no signatures can pass the tests that are imposed by that particular schema context that is running on a XAML object writer.","pos":[13069,13231]},{"content":"By default, <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Xaml.XamlSchemaContextSettings.SupportMarkupExtensionsWithDuplicateArity%2A&gt;</ph> is <ph id=\"ph2\">`false`</ph> in the CLR-based <ph id=\"ph3\">&lt;xref:System.Xaml.XamlSchemaContext&gt;</ph> for .NET Framework XAML Services.","pos":[13238,13438],"source":"By default, <xref:System.Xaml.XamlSchemaContextSettings.SupportMarkupExtensionsWithDuplicateArity%2A> is `false` in the CLR-based <xref:System.Xaml.XamlSchemaContext> for .NET Framework XAML Services."},{"content":"Thus, the default <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Xaml.XamlObjectWriter&gt;</ph> throws exceptions if it encounters a markup extension usage where there is duplicate arity in the backing type's constructors.","pos":[13439,13619],"source":" Thus, the default <xref:System.Xaml.XamlObjectWriter> throws exceptions if it encounters a markup extension usage where there is duplicate arity in the backing type's constructors."},{"pos":[13692,13737],"content":"Named Arguments for a Custom Markup Extension","linkify":"Named Arguments for a Custom Markup Extension","nodes":[{"content":"Named Arguments for a Custom Markup Extension","pos":[0,45]}]},{"content":"Markup extensions as specified by XAML can also use a named arguments form for usage.","pos":[13741,13826]},{"content":"At the first level of tokenization, the text syntax is divided into arguments.","pos":[13827,13905]},{"content":"The presence of an equals sign (=) within any argument identifies an argument as a named argument.","pos":[13906,14004]},{"content":"Such an argument is also tokenized into a name/value pair.","pos":[14005,14063]},{"content":"The name in this case names a public settable property of the markup extension's support type.","pos":[14064,14158]},{"content":"If you intend to support named argument usage, you should provide these public settable properties.","pos":[14159,14258]},{"content":"The properties can be inherited properties as long as they remain public.","pos":[14259,14332]},{"pos":[14433,14506],"content":"Accessing Service Provider Context from a Markup Extension Implementation","linkify":"Accessing Service Provider Context from a Markup Extension Implementation","nodes":[{"content":"Accessing Service Provider Context from a Markup Extension Implementation","pos":[0,73]}]},{"content":"The services available are the same for an